The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) is issuing a travel warning to people of color planning to travel to Missouri due to discriminatory policies and racist attacks in the state.
“The NAACP Missouri Travel Advisory, effective August 28, 2017, calls on all African American travelers, tourists, and Missourians to be advised when traveling in Missouri due to the recent series of suspicious racial incidents in Missouri. Special attention and an attitude of extreme caution are hereby advised,” the group’s statement declared.
The NAACP cited a recently passed Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits and state enforcement that has disproportionately targeted minorities, prompting the organization to issue the travel warning.
Civil rights violations are happening to people.
They were pulled over, beaten or killed because of the color of their skin,&quot; Missouri NAACP President Rod Chappell told The Kansas City Star.
&quot;We&#39;ve received an unprecedented number of complaints.&quot;
This is the first such warning issued by the group for a state in the United States.
The group cited racial slurs against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year. He ran out of gas while traveling in Missouri and was detained by Missouri State Police without being charged with a crime.
The advisory also points to a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General&#39;s Office showing that &quot;black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped and searched compared to white drivers.&quot;
&quot;This advisory is to raise awareness and warn their family, friends and co-workers of what may be happening in Missouri,&quot; Chappell said.
&quot;People need to be prepared, whether traveling to Missouri with bail money or letting relatives know they are traveling within the state.&quot;
According to the latest data from the FBI&#39;s Hate Crime Reporting Program, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015; ranking the state 16th in the nation based on the number of crimes.
The travel warning is also in response to a new Missouri law that would make it more difficult to sue businesses for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, U.S. states passed immigration enforcement laws requiring local law enforcement to detain immigration violators. The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) said the move would increase the number of racial lawsuits and issued travel advisories for Texas and Arizona. .
Travel warnings are typically issued by the U.S. government for other countries, but more recently, advisory groups have adopted this approach in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
