One picture to understand: Bitcoin’s legal status around the world
Abstract: In addition to the price correction naturally caused by speculative attributes, this round of digital currency’s sharp decline is also related to the “old enemy”—regulatory risk.
Judging from the visual map, Eastern countries have a more conservative attitude toward Bitcoin than the West. Countries that account for the majority of the world are still waiting to see the legality of digital currencies, which means that &quot;black swan risks&quot; are still very high.
*This article comes from Wall Street News (WeChat ID: wallstreetcn), edited by Wang Mu. For more exciting information, please visit wallstreetcn.com, or download the Wall Street Insights APP. *
As regulatory storms arise in major Bitcoin markets such as China, South Korea and the European Union, global digital currencies led by Bitcoin have suffered a bloodbath this week. The price of Bitcoin fell below the psychological round number of US$10,000 on Tuesday, reaching its highest level in three years. Biggest one-day drop.
In addition to price corrections naturally caused by speculative attributes, this round of sharp decline in digital currencies is also related to regulatory risks, which have always been the &quot;old enemy&quot;.
At this important juncture, the visual big data website HowMuch.net produced a map showing the legal status and degree of regulation of Bitcoin in countries around the world.
As shown in the figure below, green represents the legal market for Bitcoin; orange represents the neutral market, although the status of Bitcoin has not been publicly legalized, but there are no major usage restrictions; light pink represents the restricted market, that is, the local government attempts to pass Red lines of policy or regulation address the use of digital currencies; dark pink represents countries where Bitcoin is defined as illegal; gray represents countries that have not yet commented.
(The above picture is from the HowMuch.Net visualization team drawing on January 15th)
The article pointed out that from the distribution of non-green color blocks in the picture, it can be seen that Eastern countries in the traditional sense have a more conservative attitude towards Bitcoin than the West.
Russia is currently the largest country that has defined Bitcoin as illegal, China is one of the largest restricted markets for Bitcoin, and India is one of the largest countries that has not yet commented on Bitcoin and has not yet introduced relevant policies.
North America and Western Europe are the regions with the highest acceptance of Bitcoin, i.e. the distribution of green blocks is more concentrated.
Countries in the Middle East and Latin America have clearly divided views on Bitcoin, and the distribution of color blocks in the above regions is more mixed.
Among them, Iraq, Iran, Turkey, and Brazil are all legal Bitcoin markets. Afghanistan, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Bolivia, etc. have certain restrictions on their transactions and use. More Latin American countries have not yet spoken out about Bitcoin.
Based on the above data, it can be seen that among the 246 countries in the world that are counted, a total of 99 countries (or 40%) impose no restrictions on the transaction and use of Bitcoin, that is, green and orange areas.
There are 7 countries (or 3%) that are restricted markets (light pink), 10 countries (or 4%) that define Bitcoin as illegal (dark pink), and 130 countries (or 53%). %) There is no further information on digital currencies (gray).
This shows that the countries that account for the majority of the world (53%, more than half) are still waiting to see the legality of digital currencies led by Bitcoin in the country. It also means that the &quot;black swan risk&quot; of Bitcoin is still very high, because some of these countries Legislative decisions to restrict digital currencies may eventually be made.
The article believes that global regulatory agencies have not fully understood the emerging category of digital currency, which may be the main reason why most countries have not yet made a statement.
Although Bitcoin&#39;s &quot;popularity&quot; has grown exponentially since last year, it does not mean that all countries are interested. Some countries may be worried that their local legal currencies will be threatened, or they may be worried that digital currencies are being used by criminal organizations.
The Wall Street Journal once wrote a detailed summary of the international regulatory news on Bitcoin since last week, including China&#39;s crackdown on centralized service online platforms and mobile apps of over-the-counter exchanges, South Korea is still considering closing digital currency exchanges, and the European Union believes that Bitcoin It has not yet been widely accepted and warns investors of the risks of &quot;losing all their money&quot;, etc.
Selected by the editor-in-chief of Wall Street News, &quot;Reading News | 2018: Will central banks around the world usher in the first year of digital currency?&quot; ” once mentioned that from any perspective of supervision, acceptance/criticism, and adoption, 2018 will be the first year of digital currency for global central banks.
Russia and other major countries’ criticism of Bitcoin’s legal status is actually to make way for the official issuance of digital currencies.
