Block critics on Facebook: Don’t run for office if you can’t stand rebuke from voters
Our Founding Fathers knew the ways of a bad press.
Americans loved Washington, but it wasn&#39;t long before newspapers began savaging him on everything from his domestic policies to his political principles.
He was annoyed by the criticism, no doubt.
But he did not silence these critics.
Because as early as 1783, Washington said, “Deprived of free speech, we shall be slaughtered like lambs in silence and ignorance.”
This brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to learn from Washington.
Hogan&#39;s staff blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people for expressing their views on his official Facebook page.
The American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit against him earlier this week.
The governor&#39;s staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and online reports were filled with their backlash: &quot;Who cares?&quot;
A lot of people say “it’s just Facebook.”
But, this is important.
This is especially important when facing someone like Hogan.
This was a Republican governor of a majority-Democratic state, and he was surprisingly popular.
Among the 50 governors in the country, he ranks second in praise.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He ran Maryland smoothly and followed the rules.
He is also very good at using Facebook as his main way to connect emotionally with voters, jokingly showing off his bald head after chemotherapy for the first time on his homepage.
So blocking people who come to the governor’s page to comment is completely unnecessary and ultimately dangerous. This page is a public forum, officially managed by a staff supported by public tax dollars.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan&#39;s spokesperson Amelia Shas defended the governor&#39;s actions, saying she believed blocking their comments was simply an attempt to show restraint.
But they are too hasty to describe them as scourges or cynics sweeping the web.
The Washington Post spoke face-to-face with people blocked by Hogan.
They are just ordinary people talking to their elected leaders: they are teachers, small business owners, and pastors, not monsters.
They all said their comments were in-depth, respectful and not obscene.
The pastor quoted Scripture in his post, calling on Hogan to remember his Catholic faith.
Barrister Lakshmi Salma Ramani of Bowie, Maryland, wasn&#39;t cynical, but she asked about hate crimes.
&quot;I politely commented that I was disappointed that he had not responded to hate crimes and other recent news incidents,&quot; she wrote in the comments section of the Washington Post news story.
I also don&#39;t like a bunch of people commenting on the same topic, because these people will be directly ignored by some people, thinking that they have a so-called herd mentality, instead of treating them as a group of citizens who care about the country and the people. &quot;
What the governor&#39;s staff calls an &quot;intense bombardment of spam&quot; may appear to others as &quot;assertiveness.&quot;
The age of Facebook makes it easy to modify a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
And it was far cleaner than in the past, when achieving the same effect would have required sending staff out to collect and burn critical newspapers or arresting or silencing protesters.
But that&#39;s exactly what&#39;s happening now, but on a digital level.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for silencing others on Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users for blocking them on Twitter.
A landmark ruling came out last week in Virginia on just such an issue.
The chairwoman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment when she blocked a voter from her Facebook page, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Katsaris of Alexandria.
Kentucky Gov. Matt Bevin (R) has also been patronized by the American Civil Liberties Union for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
This shouldn&#39;t be this hard.
In the Washington era, affordable postage and the Internet had a similar impact.
The number of newspapers quadrupled between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letters fiercely criticized his leadership.
And even then, there were anonymous scourges targeting him in Washington.
People wrote letters to newspapers using pseudonyms such as Eureka, Valerius, Belisarius, and Pogius, severely criticizing Washington&#39;s decision-making.
His office was inundated with petitions criticizing his stance on the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce, and Navigation between His Majesty the King of England and the United States of America, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Newspapers Online Project.
But he did not silence them.
Freedom of speech, freedom of dissent and freedom of speech are the foundation of this country.
And true leaders need to accept this.
