Poverty and death in Indonesia&#39;s Golden Island
Badina Deij doesn&#39;t use a stove when she cooks.
She rarely even uses the pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai district in Indonesia&#39;s Papua province, the housewife usually just puts a sweet potato - known locally as a &quot;nota&quot; - directly into the fire.
Half an hour later, the burnt sweet potato was eagerly taken out by a pair of unwashed hands and devoured.
Daijie sat on the dirt floor - she had no furniture - and this was where she did daily household chores, such as washing clothes in murky water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room is the outhouse.
She was the youngest of her husband&#39;s four wives, so she was not assigned fields to tend.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, many are drunk, and there are a lot of soldiers here.
&quot;No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m.,&quot; she said.
It&#39;s a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia following a controversial 1969 referendum in which just 1,026 elders were forced to vote in front of occupying troops. Hands vote.
The current movement for independence and opposition to Dutch rule quickly turned its back on Jakarta&#39;s government, which has imposed a repressive rule on the region and cut off foreign journalists and rights activists.
In 2003, the province officially split into Papua and West Papua provinces, with Papua New Guinea independently controlling the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is remote and uninhabited; to get here you need to take a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire, then rent a car and drive for 5 hours, making your stomach churn all the way.
There is no public transportation here.
In this town of about 19,000 people, wooden houses are surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated iron roofs are various shades of tawny rust.
Few Indonesians come here, let alone journalists, and almost no foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, Mee Pago Papuans believed in a god called Uga Tamee.
There are other changes here, too.
“We can’t get used to wearing these clothes,” Daijie said, referring to her brightly colored handwoven headscarf, dark blouse and bright skirt.
&quot;We used to just cover ourselves with leaves.&quot;
Papua is Indonesia&#39;s poorest province, with 28% of people living below the poverty line. It also has the highest infant mortality rate and the lowest literacy rate in Asia.
But this is also the golden island of Indonesia.
Paniai County is located in the highlands, is about the same size as New Jersey, and has a population of 153,000 people. Just 60 miles away is Grasberg, the world&#39;s largest and most profitable gold mine, owned by Phoenix-based Philip McMoRan Copper and Gold.
In 2015 alone, Felipe mined approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua is rich in timber resources, estimated to be worth US$78 billion.
However, these rich resources are also the source of tragedy for the Papuans. This is why Indonesia&#39;s powerful military power has been able to suppress them.
A 2005 New York Times investigative report revealed that Phillip paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and troops between 1998 and 2004, including as much as $150,000 to a single official.
The Papuans&#39; growing demands for independence threatened the benefactor, and they were subjected to brutal treatment.
According to rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by Indonesian troops.
Mass killings in Papua&#39;s tribal highlands in the 1970s escalated into genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters.
A 2016 report from the Catholic Archdiocese of Brisbane, &quot;We Have Everything to Lose,&quot; included evidence of the previous year&#39;s egregious crimes, such as extrajudicial killings and torture - another report said rape and electrocution were particularly common. — and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
&quot;Violence occurs every day, making it difficult to count the number of victims,&quot; said Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher at Human Rights Watch.
Oppression began when Papua&#39;s resources attracted large numbers of immigrants from outside Indonesia.
83% of the province&#39;s 3.5 million people are Christians, but its demographic structure has changed since Muslim economic immigrants arrived here from the densely populated islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese food stalls sell gado gado mixed with fried chicken and vegetables, served with peanut sauce.
Locals fought hard.
&quot;The immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,&quot; explains Apos Yu, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura to find work.
This deprived the local Papuans - Papuan women (mama-mama) - of their market. &quot;
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, often known as Jokowi, vowed during his 2014 election campaign to tackle inequality and abuse of power in Papua.
The former carpenter&#39;s path to the presidential palace in Jakarta was supported by 27 out of 29 regions - including Paniai.
But nothing has changed in Papua, and today locals feel betrayed.
&quot;We are heartbroken and we voted for Jokowi in 2014 in the hope that he would fulfill our wishes and restore fairness,&quot; You said.
In fact, just two months after Jokowi took office in October, Paniai encountered his worst nightmare.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children in Enarotali were singing Christmas carols in front of a bonfire outside when two Indonesian soldiers suddenly rushed over on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them they should turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers was dissatisfied with their tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavit Tebai.
Victims and witnesses said the drunken soldiers chased the children and beat them with the butts of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers opened fire on the group of children.
Julianus Yemo, 16, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
Hours later, a raging fire broke out at the Electoral Commission building, a nearby government agency, and the incident escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered at a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
Carrying ceremonial hunting bows, they danced the waita dance of Papua&#39;s Mee Pago tribe - running in circles and imitating bird song.
Some protesters began throwing stones at regular military posts.
As emotions continued to escalate, soldiers received orders via internal radio: &quot;If the crowd resists more than three times, they will be shot immediately,&quot; according to an official document seen by TIME. The document was not released to local media.
Sensing imminent danger, 56-year-old Yeremias Kayamu, chief of the Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, called on the crowd to calm down and implored them to go home.
But no one was in the mood to listen to him.
&quot;When I turned around, I was shot in the left wrist,&quot; he told TIME while standing on the porch of his brightly painted log house.
Kayamu still doesn&#39;t know who fired the shot, but he said the bullet came from among the gathered soldiers.
He added, &quot;It was very crowded and they fired a lot of shots.&quot;
According to the cousin of local Orfuyus Yule, he witnessed the shooting and saw Orfuyus Yuhl was shot three times.
&quot;I ran over to check on him to see if it was him,&quot; Yohanes sadly told Time magazine.
I found him dead...I kissed him. &quot;
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yogi Mende told reporters that his subordinates were only &quot;protecting&quot; the police station because it was under attack.
In 2015, Papua police spokesman Police Chief Pugio Sulistio said “When someone threatens to kill us, we must defend ourselves.
This is a matter of life and death. &quot;
Five young protesters were killed and many more were injured, according to Human Rights Watch.
News of the killing spread only slowly in Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an emotional speech in Jayapura, expressing deep sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address Papua&#39;s legacy of abuses.
&quot;I hope this case can be resolved as soon as possible so that something like this doesn&#39;t happen again in the future,&quot; he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wirando stated that he would establish a non-judicial mechanism to resolve the historical issue of human rights violations.
But the excuses came out almost immediately.
&quot;Most of the violations happened a long time ago,&quot; he said.
Some were in the 90s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations, but this is a process. &quot;
Then on June 5 in Jakarta, Wilando went back on his words in a conversation with Time magazine, saying he had no plans to establish a grievance mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said &quot;everything will be resolved in accordance with the law.&quot;
The United Nations has charged Wilando with &quot;crimes against human rights&quot; over the deaths of more than 1,000 people during East Timor&#39;s bloody 1999 independence vote, but he said 11 cases of human rights abuses in Papua have been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
Relatives of the victims of the Paniai incident scoffed at these remarks.
&quot;I&#39;ve been interviewed four times in the last three years and things haven&#39;t progressed at all,&quot; Yohanes said.
Years later he said &quot;I&#39;m tired.&quot;
He still lives in fear.
&quot;I&#39;m scared,&quot; he said.
I was afraid of being arrested by the military, of being shot. &quot;
His brother Yukabus also believes that the people of Paniai are afraid to talk about the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping bury four victims.
&quot;After burying the body, the military came to see me,&quot; he said.
The shooting didn&#39;t stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in Deyai district, a neighboring county in Paniai.
A construction company manager refused to help transport an unconscious man to hospital, resulting in a clash that left one person dead and 17 others injured, including children.
Lavianus Dove, a 24-year-old man, drowned while fishing in a nearby river and died on the way to hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company&#39;s field office.
Police said villagers threw rocks at police, so officers fired warning shots.
But the Riot Mobile Unit (Indonesian paramilitary police) began shooting into the crowd, and one person was killed.
“We all panicked and now we’re afraid they will retaliate,” Domingo Badi, 29, who lives near the hospital and watched the wounded being rushed into the hospital, told Time magazine.
&quot;I hid at home for two days.&quot;
The Deyayi parliament has called for the police officers involved to be brought to justice and for the anti-riot mobile unit to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a place of contention for the Indonesian government.
The lack of effective development has fostered dissatisfaction among the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribal people, who are scattered across Paniai&#39;s lush central highlands.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans through scattered attacks and raids to kidnap Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top leaders of the Free Papua Movement were born in Paniai, including Tadeus Yogi and Daniel Yodas Kogoa.
As a result, thousands of Paniai people have been arrested and deliberately detained by the military in recent years under the guise of &quot;maintaining national sovereignty.&quot;
Some were never seen again.
In the eyes of Papuans, Paniai is a &quot;forgotten tragic place&quot;.
Poverty breeds dissatisfaction.
There is so little rice for sale in Enarotali that locals cannot afford it.
Bread was simply out of reach.
People here grow everything they can eat: mostly sweet potatoes and some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming was women&#39;s work, and each woman tended four or five sweet potato plots.
They usually keep most of their harvest for home use and sell the remainder in local markets.
Ten pieces of sweet potato cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupiah (75 US cents).
Over time, economic inequality has widened between local Papuans and new immigrants, whose numbers have increased significantly since the new route to Nabire Airport opened.
The few jobs that existed generally went to better-educated and wealthier immigrants.
Few Papuans have the capital or the necessary skills to run competitive companies.
&quot;Young people don&#39;t want to stay in this village... because there are no jobs and no money here,&quot; said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Papua is isolated.
In addition, restrictions on international media coverage remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basel Longchamp were expelled from Papua because they &quot;failed to cooperate with the relevant authorities&quot; even though they had received rare authorization to film.
Jokowi&#39;s election vow to lift reporting restrictions to promote transparency and development has not been fulfilled, according to Felim Kane, deputy Asia director at Human Rights Watch.
&quot;If foreign journalists try to cover Indonesia&#39;s disaffected easternmost provinces of Papua and West Papua, they face new risks: visa denial and blacklisting,&quot; he said in a statement.
The lack of media scrutiny means international pressure on the Indonesian government has been largely limited to Papua&#39;s neighbors.
In March, six Pacific countries - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, the Solomon Islands - asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate &quot;widespread human rights violations&quot; in Papua, including the Paniai shooting case.
These countries also supported the Free Papua Movement.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesperson Armanata Nasir was dismissive of the group&#39;s accusations, telling reporters in Jakarta that &quot;Indonesia still operates a democratic system and has a free media, so it is difficult to cover up evidence of human rights violations.&quot; .”
Locals want more foreign governments to take notice.
When Dutch human rights ambassador Keith Van Baar led a delegation of officials to Jayapura on May 4, local people broke their silence and begged, “We want freedom,” according to a person familiar with the matter who also attended. attended the meeting but requested anonymity.
Indonesia will hold its next presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
Tribal Council Chairman Gobai said &quot;Jokowi has good intentions, but he is surrounded by people who were involved in the Paniai shooting.&quot;
He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai not only live under threat from a greedy military, but also have nothing, a region with little education and little public health care.
Gobai said the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, view their vote for Jokowi as a debt he must repay.
&quot;They don&#39;t want money, they want justice,&quot; he said.
Even in the face of threats and intimidation, the families of the Paniai shooting victims still made their last symbolic act of resistance: burying a victim&#39;s body opposite the military police post.
They know justice may never come, but at least they won&#39;t let those responsible forget their crimes.
Yukabus lowered his head and said, &quot;My family was killed;
What else can we do? &quot;
