Moore Beach massacre: Activists recreate racist lynching, demand justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury rumbles past a crowd of onlookers in the small town of Monroe, Georgia, toward the tiny Moore Ford Bridge.
Before the car reached the bridge, carrying four black passengers and a white driver, a group of white men with guns stepped forward and blocked the car&#39;s path.
The leader of the gang - a middle-aged man in a pinstriped suit - took a deep drag on his cigar and glanced through the windshield.
The passengers in the car were filled with fear.
&quot;We want - Roger!&quot; the man shouted.
&quot;Get him out of the car!&quot;
Screams pierced the silence as a young black man was dragged from the front passenger seat.
Fortunately, this horrific scene on July 22 was just a repeat.
However, when the noose was placed around &quot;Roger&#39;s&quot; neck, almost all the spectators let out a real gasp.
Since 2005, civil rights activists have returned to the Moore Ford Bridge to reenact the night two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mery Dorsey - were lynched and hanged by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946 .
No one has ever been charged with murder.
&quot;Even though we know who they are, even though we see them in the community, it&#39;s incredible that none of them have been arrested over the years,&quot; said Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the reenactment.
&quot;This is a stain on history and a burden on our souls.&quot;
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia congressman and lifelong rights activist.
For him, the reenactment serves as a compelling call to action, an annual reminder to those in the Monroe community of injustices that are never righted.
&quot;We want to prosecute, we want closure, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but we have to get justice first,&quot; he said.
&quot;Unless we get justice, we won&#39;t get healing and reconciliation.&quot;
The coroner covers the body of a Moore Beach lynching victim with a sheet on July 27, 1946.
More than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties are suspected of participating in the lynching, according to FBI files obtained by NBC News.
But none of them were ever prosecuted.
While the suspects have remained at large for decades, civil rights activists say the twin motivations for the lynchings were known throughout town: political and sexual.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling allowed Georgia&#39;s black citizens to vote in primary elections for the first time later that summer.
Around the same time, black sharecropper Roger Malcolm assassinated white landowner Barnett Hearst during a fight — seemingly over a woman, according to the FBI.
Brooks said the rumor around town was that Hester slept with Malcolm&#39;s wife, Dorothy, and that her baby was not her husband&#39;s.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Roy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to bail Malcolm out of jail.
Dorothy and cousins Mai Murray and George Dorsey accompanied him to the prison.
But as they returned from prison and approached Moore&#39;s Beach Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
&quot;As it turned out, it was Harrison who organized and ordered the murder,&quot; an FBI report concluded.
&quot;It is clear that there was a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement who not only participated in the murders, destroyed evidence, and concealed the identities of witnesses.&quot;
Brooks is very succinct.
“This is a voting rights tragedy,” he said.
&quot;Their brutal murders sent a message to black people in this community: &#39;If you register and vote, the same thing will happen to you.&#39;&quot;
Cassandra Greene has been leading the annual reenactment of the Moore Beach Bridge lynching for nearly a decade.
Her expression is vivid and gripping, with a deeply racist background. Many people wish this type of racism no longer existed in America.
It&#39;s hard to watch, and even harder not to watch, but Green says that&#39;s the point.
&quot;We don&#39;t want to talk about lynching because lynching makes us face the ugly side of everyone,&quot; she said.
&quot;But I can&#39;t have a relationship with you if you don&#39;t listen to me or hear me tell my story.&quot;
This year&#39;s show began in June, and on the first day nearly 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - crowded into a room and listened as Green delivered an overview of the rehearsed show.
Wade Marble serves as Green&#39;s co-director.
He&#39;s played the role of a Klansman for years, but he says the role has never been easy.
&quot;I feel dirty because that&#39;s not who I am,&quot; Marbaugh said.
“But I think it’s important to keep this history alive because we don’t want to go back to that era.”
In the room, actors Darios Bradshaw and Nick Lascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hearst, rehearse their lines.
The scene begins with Malcolm yelling and pushing Hester away, furious that he slept with his wife, Dorothy.
&quot;I said, get out of my territory!&quot;
Lascona shot back.
Then they started fighting.
Then everyone (at least all the black actors) burst out laughing.
Green laughed the hardest.
&quot;What happened?!,&quot; Lascona asked.
He was panicked and confused.
Have I overacted?
&quot;No,&quot; Green said with a smile.
&quot;I just don&#39;t think white people say &#39;ugh&#39; when they say that back.&quot;
&quot;Yeah,&quot; another black actor quipped.
&quot;You have to sound strong.&quot;
Just like that, the energy in the room shifted; the feeling of camaraderie drove away the discomfort.
Everyone strives to do so not only to perform the scene but also to honor the four victims.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Lascona said the word &quot;Ah,&quot; his tone was sharp and forceful.
No one laughed.
The reenactment ended powerfully and quickly.
There were screams, gunfire, and then, silence.
A woman in funeral black stood next to the actor&#39;s body and sang Billie Holiday&#39;s eulogy &quot;Strange Fruit.&quot;
Her voice spoke above all other words.
A hundred yards away, about forty spectators were wiping away sweat and tears.
The audience was almost evenly split between blacks and whites.
A couple traveled from Ithaca, New York, to see the show, and many others lived just down the road.
Brooks took them to visit Malcolm and Dorothy&#39;s gravesite, a nearly eight-hour journey, all enduring the uncomfortable humidity of Georgia.
To this day, the murderer remains a mystery. But now, standing on the same ground where the lynching took place, anxiety is in the air.
As the final notes of the song faded, Green asked people to come closer and examine the actor&#39;s corpse.
The children hunched over the fake blood and corpses, whispering to each other.
&quot;They&#39;re not really dead,&quot; a little boy muttered, as if to remind himself.
After a few minutes, Green thanked the crowd and the show ended.
The actor shook off the lynching rope and wiped away tears.
Bradshaw hugged Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the Ku Klux Klan leader.
Nick Lascona hugged two of his colleagues and cried in their arms; the emotion of the performance eventually got to him.
&quot;It&#39;s okay,&quot; one of the women whispered.
&quot;We know that&#39;s not what&#39;s going on in your heart.
You do this for a reason. &quot;
Afterwards, the audience sat down to dine with the actors.
At the same table, a white couple from Atlanta chatted intimately about reenactments with a black couple they had just met.
Denise Duplinski struggled to find words to describe how she felt after watching it.
&quot;It&#39;s hard to imagine that those horrific words and actions ... could be said and done by someone like you because they look so much like you,&quot; she said.
&quot;That, to me, really makes me think that lynchings are still going on,&quot; she added, &quot;and now it&#39;s just called police shootings.&quot;
Inside the room, Tyrone Brooks sat at the table watching, savoring and reminiscing about civil rights.
He said he&#39;s already starting to plan next year&#39;s show.
“The reenactment is inspiring because it describes the horrors we experienced, but it’s also very educational,” he said.
“If you don’t learn from this, it could happen again.
Those who do not study and understand their own history are doomed to repeat the same mistakes. &quot;
