US media: Scientists from China&#39;s Air Force Engineering University study laser satellites to remove space debris
Reference News Network reported on January 18 that US media said that Chinese scientists have put forward a bold and innovative proposal to use large lasers to clean up the cluttered Earth orbit and destroy old satellites and their sky debris.
According to a report on the US Newsweek website on January 15, researchers from the Air Force Engineering University of China wrote a paper titled &quot;Research on Orbital Change Model for Space-Based Laser Clearance of Small-Scale Space Debris&quot;. The paper describes how to use space-based laser to remove small-scale space debris. Based on platform lasers, how space debris can be irradiated by lasers into smaller, less harmful debris.
According to reports, space debris has been a concern for international space agencies for many years, and NASA has considered a variety of options to track, detect and remove man-made debris.
Ways to remove large-scale space debris include giant nets to sweep and collect waste, and magnets that can be used to suck them out of orbit. Chinese scientists conducted laser simulation studies and came to the conclusion that this would be an effective way to clean up the Earth&#39;s orbit.
The abstract of the paper states: &quot;(Simulation research) provides the necessary theoretical basis for the application of laser space debris removal technology on space-based platforms.&quot;
A 2014 study by U.S. defense giant Lockheed Martin found that there are approximately 200 threats to satellites in orbit every day.
High-speed debris moving along the Earth&#39;s orbit is regarded as a serious threat to future space missions and has been described by experts from the European Space Agency as a &quot;deadly chain of threats.&quot; High-velocity debris continues to increase with every passing year.
According to a report on the website of the American monthly magazine Popular Mechanics on January 17, space is basically empty, but the space next to the earth is becoming more and more crowded. Every satellite we send into space ends up being just another piece of debris orbiting the Earth, and over time, the debris accumulates.
The more debris there is, the higher the chance that a functioning satellite will be hit by debris, damaging or destroying a multi-million dollar investment.
According to reports, all space agencies have formulated plans to remove space debris in the future.
NASA is considering using jet gas to slow down the debris and deorbit it. Europe is considering launching a satellite carrying a large net to capture the debris and bring it back to Earth. Japan&#39;s idea is to use an electric chain to capture the debris.
At present, China has also proposed a solution to space junk, which is to use a large laser to break floating space junk into small, less harmful fragments.
Installing such a laser on a satellite would be effective enough to clean up space, at least according to simulations, according to a paper published in the German monthly Optics by a group of researchers from China&#39;s Air Force Engineering University.
According to reports, the only way to confirm effectiveness is to conduct tests. There are currently no such missions planned, but perhaps sooner or later someone will install a laser on a satellite and send it into space.
Once we do that, we can finally begin to eliminate the space junk problem once and for all.
