Latest results of age assessment test for Swedish asylum seekers released
The latest results from Swedish tests of asylum seekers using the latest method to medically assess their age show that more than 80% of the subjects were judged to be over 18 years old, but not everyone is convinced of its accuracy.
Sweden&#39;s National Center for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) began testing earlier this year.
The tests were designed by the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) to provide a more accurate age assessment during the asylum process, after being accused of failing to accurately assess the age of some refugees claiming to be minors.
So far, the Swedish Immigration Service has sent 6,880 test takers, and the Forensic Medicine Center has now published the results of a total of 2,481 test takers between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
80% (2,002 people) were judged to be 18 years or older, but in another 25 cases, the Swedish National Center for Forensic Medicine determined that the subjects &quot;may be 18 years or older.&quot;
In 432 cases, the result was that the person was &quot;probably under 18 years of age.&quot;
The test is only for people whose age is in question.
According to John Grantson of the Center for Forensic Science, these results are consistent with those from previous months.
&quot;The figures are not that different from previous months, the numbers are very consistent,&quot; he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases where people are judged to be over 18 years old does not necessarily mean that these asylum seekers have lied about their age.
In May, the center released test results from 581 cases, saying 442 &quot;indicated the subject was 18 years of age or older.&quot;
Newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the results of 581 tests published this time and found that 243 of the subjects had publicly stated that they would turn 18 this year.
X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of joints, with the results analyzed by dentists and radiologists, are also being questioned in some quarters.
One of those skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing people&#39;s biological maturity to determine whether they are going through puberty earlier or later than normal.
He told news paper Metro: &quot;I have reason to think that and I don&#39;t think the measurement used should be that way.
Determining biological age in this way is highly inaccurate.
If we can&#39;t guarantee accuracy, we shouldn&#39;t pretend that we can. &quot;
Yet Grantson of the Center for Forensic Medicine defends the accuracy of the tests: &quot;In general it can be said that the risk of uncertainty in declaring a child an adult is small.&quot;
The greatest risk is that the person is under 18, which occurs about 10% of the time.
