What impact will football&#39;s financial rules have on Neymar&#39;s move to Paris Saint-Germain?
Rules designed to prevent unrestricted spending by Europe&#39;s top football clubs will not hinder Neymar&#39;s record-breaking move from Spain&#39;s FC Barcelona to France&#39;s Paris Saint-Germain (PSG).
The consequence was that the Union of European Football Associations (UEFA) further downgraded the Paris Saint-Germain Football Club. The Union of European Football Associations, the governing body of European football competitions, has the power to ban teams from participating in the widely watched Champions League.
The introduction of Financial Fair Play (FFP) by UEFA in 2011 meant that PSG would eventually have to prove that Neymar&#39;s transfer was funded without incurring a huge loss.
FC Barcelona has paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to cover the Brazilian player&#39;s release fee, and Neymar&#39;s salary will be tens of millions of dollars per year.
Here are some of the financial implications of Neymar&#39;s move to France.
Given that the team is funded by Qatar&#39;s deep-pocketed ruling family, PSG could certainly use the cash to sign Neymar and add him to its other star-studded squad.
Clubs can spend huge sums of money to buy players, but they must use legitimate revenue sources to make up for the huge sums spent, allowing them to break even on football-related operations.
The Financial Fair Play Rules were an idea proposed by Michel Platini after he was elected as UEFA president in 2007.
The former France player believes that for clubs that have racked up debt in their pursuit of success, they are effectively cheating and risking their destruction if banks or owners withdraw support.
In 2011, the focus of the Rules shifted from club debt issues to the monitoring of club losses.
The change means that the business model used by Roman Abramovich when he bought Chelsea in 2003 was to buy a club with potential, then spend huge sums to improve the team and build it into a global Brands are now facing a more demanding situation.
Over the three-year Code review period ending in 2018, clubs could lose €30 million.
Although Abramovich was disparaged by his then-president in 2015, UEFA successor Aleksander Ceferin remains committed to stemming excessive spending.
&quot;Of course the Code has not expired and we will definitely strengthen the regulations in the future,&quot; UEFA&#39;s Andrea Traverso, who is responsible for the Code, told The Associated Press last week.
While PSG will pay Neymar&#39;s buyout clause in a lump sum, it can also distribute the amount for accounting purposes over the life of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year deal, so the transfer fee will likely show up as a fee of €44.4 million in annual accounts for the next five years.
The first wave of Code sanctions, imposed in 2014, saw Paris Saint-Germain, as well as Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City, hit with the toughest sanctions.
Paris Saint-Germain was fined 60 million euros ($82 million at the time of exchange), later reduced to 20 million euros, and ordered to reduce its roster to 21 players in the 2014-15 Champions League. Instead of the normal 25 players.
UEFA is eyeing clubs trying to deceive financial regulators by tying themselves to owners to boost revenue.
While Qatari companies can sponsor Paris Saint-Germain, UEFA will not consider it legitimate income if the amount is deemed to exceed standard market value.
This is what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the amount paid by Qatar Tourism Authority to sponsor Paris Saint-Germain was inflated.
According to reports, part of Neymar&#39;s earnings at Paris Saint-Germain could come from payments from the organizing committee for the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
However, PSG and the organizing committee have both denied that Neymar will serve as a World Cup ambassador, and it would be easy for UEFA&#39;s governing body to make such a move.
The recent sanctions imposed on Paris Saint-Germain mean that UEFA will be even more vigilant about any attempts to circumvent the rules.
UEFA has not held pre-discussions with Paris Saint-Germain over a transfer for Neymar, sources familiar with the matter said on Thursday.
The people spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to discuss the situation at PSG.
The last published accounts showed that Paris Saint-Germain Football Club had operating income of 542.4 million euros in 2015-16 and a profit of more than 10 million euros.
Accounts for the previous financial year have not yet been published.
Paris Saint-Germain expects Neymar&#39;s arrival to be a boon for sponsorships, franchises and jersey sales.
The club expects revenue to increase by at least 30% after signing Neymar.
Clearly outraged to see its most famous player leave, the Spanish league sought to block Neymar&#39;s move, claiming PSG had breached the Rules.
&quot;This is a clear example of &#39;financial doping&#39;, both for the club and the country,&quot; La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Paris Saint-Germain&#39;s final possession Ownership of Qatar.
Arsene Wenger, the manager of Arsenal (the club is owned by an American sports tycoon), has reservations about state-funded clubs and La Liga.
&quot;This is a consequence of ownership, which has completely changed the whole ecology of football in the last 15 years,&quot; Wenger said on Thursday.
