The Bank of England will maintain interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England will announce later that interest rates will remain unchanged, after weak economic growth and loose inflation have dashed hopes of an increase.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain &quot;weak&quot; as it tightens the squeeze on household incomes while keeping interest rates in check.
Policymakers on the bank&#39;s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep interest rates at 0.25%, while a handful of members this month called for higher rates even as weak economic growth has dampened support for an increase.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank of England scaled back its growth forecasts for 2017 and 2018 to 1.7% and 1.6% respectively, warning that the squeeze on household incomes would continue while inflation would surge to nearly 3% in the autumn.
But it said interest rates would need to rise over the next few years to curb inflation from Brexit, while borrowing costs may need to rise more sharply than expected in financial markets.
Members also voted to withdraw a massive economic stimulus package implemented a year ago due to Brexit.
The Bank of England will announce the suspension of its term financing scheme, which will provide banks with cheap funds from February next year, although the bank said that under the scheme, it currently needs an additional 15 billion pounds on top of 115 billion pounds.
In the minutes of the interest rate decision meeting, the Bank of England said: &quot;In the MPC&#39;s core forecast, gross domestic product (GDP) remains weak in the near term, as a contraction in real household incomes will continue to suppress consumption.&quot;
On interest rates, the bank reiterated that &quot;some monetary policy tightening&quot; is needed to tamp down inflation, and that it needs to be &quot;to a greater extent&quot; than markets expect.
The market is currently expecting the first growth to occur in the third quarter of next year and the second in 2020.
But the bank stressed that any increase would be &quot;slow&quot; and &quot;restrained.&quot;
The bank&#39;s growth forecasts for this year and next are trending downward, compared with forecasts in May of 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank maintained its forecast for 2018 growth of 1.8%.
The pound fell against the dollar, with the euro not far behind.
Sterling fell 0.5% against the dollar to hit 1.31 and fell 0.4% against the euro to hit 1.11.
The no-change decision came after growing expectations for an upgrade were dashed by recent dismal growth data. GDP increased to 0.3% in the second quarter, compared with 0.2% in the first three months.
The bank said growth in the third quarter was likely to remain at 0.3%, although it would rise slightly by the end of the year.
Ordinary households have been hit by soaring inflation and negligible wage growth, and the Bank of England&#39;s latest inflation report did not bring good news as it said austerity will get worse before it gets better.
It said monetary policy &quot;cannot prevent&quot; the hit to incomes in the next few years, but wages were expected to recover &quot;significantly&quot; by the end of the three-year forecast.
At the same time, because of the depreciation of the pound, demand for British goods has increased significantly, and the economy will be stimulated, offsetting part of the impact of low consumption.
The decision comes a year after a shock EU referendum sent sterling plummeting and interest rates cut to 0.25% in August.
The Bank of England estimates it could take four years to fully have an impact on prices and the UK economy.
Even before the bank announced its latest interest rate ruling, there had been calls for a rate hike as inflation worsened for already-stressed households, with three policymakers calling for an increase to 0.5% in July.
Inflation eased to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June, although the Bank of England said this was expected and would rise again in the coming months.
The bank said the excess over its 2% target was already the bottom line for a weak pound.
