NHS gives green light to controversial HIV drug
Patients will be able to access &quot;transformative&quot; HIV prevention treatments from September after the High Court settled a decision on NHS funding of the drug.
NHS England has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a drug that can be taken before sex, has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in high-risk groups by around 86%. The health service will now offer the drug to an estimated 10,000 people in an initial three-year trial.
It agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a High Court ruling last year. The ruling said the NHS has the power to pay for PrEP, despite claims that local authorities should fund the drug.
The move announced on Thursday was hailed as a &quot;significant new intervention&quot; by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a &quot;critical moment&quot;.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to register people. More clinics will join in October, before full rollout across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medication taken before sexual intercourse to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Trials have shown that PrEP can significantly reduce HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means your body has enough of the specific medicine to prevent HIV infection.
This medication can be taken daily or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay, bisexual men, transgender people and HIV-positive people who have not successfully received treatment.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who agree to the trial, including men, women, transgender people, and people whose sex partners’ HIV status is unknown and whether they are receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and are registered with a GP can also sign up at their local participating sexual health clinic.
The scheme will cost £10m and NHS England signed a contract this week to procure the drugs following an international competitive procurement process.
The trial aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how it is targeted, uptake and implemented on a large sample basis.
Mr Stevens said: “This major new intervention should complement and enhance the broad and increasingly successful approach to HIV prevention.
This is another milestone in more than 30 years of worthy action making progress in solving humanity&#39;s major health challenges. &quot;
Deborah King, chief executive of the British AIDS Trust (NAT), said: “This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
If it does target those in need and at risk, pre-exposure prophylaxis offers the potential to transform the UK&#39;s HIV epidemic.
From September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to a licensed new tool through an NHS-funded trial in England that can be administered independently without consultation with a sexual partner. Improvements in the lives of many, many people.
We applaud this announcement. &quot;
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: &quot;The priority now is to ensure trials are rolled out quickly across the country and no one living with HIV is left behind.
Now that we have purchased the PrEP trial drug, we are ready to protect more than 10,000 people at high risk for HIV. &quot;
Shadow Public Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: &quot;After months of delays and government foot-dragging, the start of the PrEP trial is welcome and should have come sooner.
Evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the spread of this deadly infection.
This trial will bring us closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is important now to roll out this trial across the country as quickly as possible to protect people exposed to HIV and help us move closer to ending the spread of HIV in society. &quot;
