Quality living: Use lofts and clever design to transform a small Earls Court apartment into a spacious home
Joanne Rae, a former banker with a passion for renovating homes, moved from her large house in Knightsbridge to a small apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of an elegant Queen Anne terrace - a testament to the new design that Joanne didn&#39;t pack it up and sell it.
&quot;Before this, I lived with my ex-boyfriend in a bigger house in Knightsbridge,&quot; Joanne said.
“I was looking for a house that matched the offer.
I saw this apartment in Earls Court and it also had very high ceilings.
I was so taken with it that I made an offer the same day. &quot;
Since the first viewing, the 1,000 sq. ft. apartment has now undergone a complete overhaul.
The apartment was originally a studio with a complicated layout - you had to walk through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - and Joanne wanted to add storage space and a loft to take advantage of the ample ceiling height.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
That’s what I ask for,” she said.
To do this, she hired Erfan Azadi of Duck &amp; Shed architecture and design studio in Notting Hill to craft a home that took advantage of the 12.5-foot-high ceilings. This home is not just a development, it is a place where Joanne lives.
The ceiling was not high enough to add two upper and lower spaces, so the architectural challenge was to create a mezzanine high enough for a person to stand.
Erfan had to think creatively so he could solve this problem.
“Steel structures are quite complex,” he explains.
“We had to arrange the space so that it was displayed up and down without having to hunch your shoulders.
It&#39;s not just as simple as building a simple platform, but starting the steel so that it&#39;s at about the right height for the function. &quot;
With this arrangement, Erfan was able to obtain two full-height rooms in the space - which could add a lot of interesting elements.
The loft features vintage copper windows by Retrouvius that overlook the charming living area.
Mirrored gold furniture, silver small furniture and Serge Mouille retro lighting establish the overall style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in adding ambience, space and light.
Add mirrors to either end of a short hallway to make it appear longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored splashback acts like a window to another room.
In the entryway, a mirrored cubby provides Joanne with storage space for cutlery and glassware.
A beautiful living room has an inviting sense of space and the ability to stow away the kitchen when not in use.
Folding kitchens are not new.
But what’s unique about this fold-down kitchen is a garage-style lift door.
“There is a bit of engineering involved,” Erfan explains of the steel-reinforced veneered MDF doors.
&quot;It&#39;s balanced so when you push the door, it slides easily.&quot;
Thanks to clever use of space and storage, Joanne gained an extra 16 square meters, an extra bedroom and an improved layout.
&quot;At the end of the day, what you&#39;re selling is the square footage of the house -- or your property valuation is based on the square footage of the house,&quot; Erfan said.
&quot;Basically, the real estate agent will go into the room and make calculations based on floor size.&quot;
They will try to increase the floor space while using high-quality materials, thus giving the space a luxurious feel.
“The materials are hand-picked by you, so they help create an emotional bond in your home,” says Erfan.
“You don’t fall in love with wall power.
These things are important, but they won&#39;t grab your heartstrings. &quot;
It turns out that with good design and the addition of extra square footage, a standard apartment can transform into something that will wow you.
In fact, you might, like Joanne, choose to stay.
