Two brothers battle for $500 million real estate empire
Forty years after their Italian family founded the dynasty, two brothers are locked in a battle for one of Victoria&#39;s largest property empires worth more than $500 million.
Former Carlton Football Club director and developer Colin De Lutis lives in a mansion in Tukara, three doors away from his brother Paul. The latter took him to the Supreme Court over the division of their real and business assets.
Paul has wanted to leave the family business since 2014, but the brothers have been locked in a fierce Supreme Court battle over the division of assets.
Together, the brothers and their mother own 38 properties worth more than $500 million, which they have accumulated since the family purchased Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans and grew it to a chain of 160 retail stores.
In 1999, the company was sold for $85 million.
That money was then invested in real estate. The De Rutis family&#39;s current portfolio includes city offices, developments in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and Mount Buller, and suburban shopping centres.
Under an agreement with his late father, Colin, described by his brother Paul as the &quot;primary mover and dominant figure&quot; in the De Lutis family, owns about two-thirds of the company&#39;s assets, while Paul owns about one third.
Documents submitted to the court stated that Colin&#39;s property was worth $316 million after conversion, while Paul&#39;s property was worth $176 million.
Paul came to believe that the division of real estate and cash proved to be a sticking point in the negotiations.
&quot;Colin&#39;s proposed property division leaves him, in my opinion, with what I consider to be the best property,&quot; he wrote in an initial court affidavit in 2015.
Last Friday, the Supreme Court held its first hearing after several failed attempts at mediation.
Now the two brothers are still fighting for control of the existing business, with Paul saying Colin has kicked him out.
Colin denied this and accused Paul of poor management of certain real estate properties.
In an early affidavit filed by Colin, he said he wanted to resolve the dispute.
&quot;My Italian heritage dictates that family is the most important option. My Italian heritage dictates that family is the most important option,&quot; he wrote.
The cost of the case continues to mount and there are hundreds of pages of affidavits, emails and submissions from firms such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, Charter Keck Cramer, top law firms such as Allan Myers, QC, and senior lawyers retained by both parties Report.
Ms. De Lutis and her late husband, Luigi, were both Italian immigrants. They have been operating a restaurant and deli since the late 1950s and bought a store in Braunschweig in the early 1970s.
They used the collateral to buy the Collingwood property, where Colin opened the family&#39;s first jeans store.
&quot;When I was a senior in high school,&quot; where he started Westco, &quot;Paul was very young (about 10 years old),&quot; Colin said.
Anna de Lutis said she and Luigi, who died in 2012, wanted to pass their fortune peacefully to their son
&quot;Luigi often told me that he never wanted his brothers to end up in court,&quot; she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis Group of Companies, with Colin saying Mark paid him $10 million and Luke $26 million when he left the company.
Paul said both Luke and Mark were &quot;dissatisfied with the terms of the division of their property.&quot;
Colin has kept a low profile despite being a former AFL club board member, according to a 2015 biography by a close friend of TV star Eddie McGuire.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul, as well as their lawyers, on Friday.
However, only Colin responded via text message. He said because the case is before the courts &quot;I can&#39;t really say much.&quot;
&quot;It is very, very sad that my brother Paul has chosen to sue me and take our family matter to court,&quot; he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a court filing that he tried to accommodate his brother&#39;s demands.
&quot;Our father would not have wanted to see Paul and I end up in a dispute like the one we are having,&quot; he said, adding that he &quot;remains hopeful that the dispute will be resolved.&quot;
On Friday, that hope seemed dashed.
&quot;Our issues will be resolved through the courts in the near future,&quot; Colin wrote.
