Trump&#39;s new chief of staff plans to limit president&#39;s media time
Others have tried and failed.
John F. Kelly might actually be able to do it.
If that&#39;s the case, then he&#39;s the first.
The new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to President Trump - including news media reporting - in an effort to keep the big boss on a more even keel, according to US political news site Politico.
Here’s an excerpt from journalist Josh Dawsey:
“As new White House chief of staff John F. Kelly began his first day on the job with senior officials, he noted that he wanted to address one of President Trump’s major problems in the White House: the flow of bad information into the president’s hands.”
Kelly told the officials that receiving good information would help the president make better decisions, which is why the information needs to be in his hands — whether in writing or in a briefing.
While Kelly&#39;s diagnosis seems plausible, others have tried and failed to tame Trump by monitoring his media time.
President Trump has a long-standing TV addiction — and now in the White House, his TV-watching habit is still growing.
“If candidate Trump is frustrated by unfair coverage, it would be helpful to let him know that he’s also getting positive coverage from credible outlets,” former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
Politico&#39;s Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that &quot;the key to reining in Trump&#39;s Twitter habits, according to the experience of six former campaign officials, is to ensure that the media messages he personally receives always include a certain amount of praise.&quot;
That&#39;s totally fine.
But the idea that Trump’s Twitter habits were ever “under control” is laughable.
Maybe these campaign officials know something we don’t—that Trump’s tweets would have been even more heated had it not been for their intervention.
We may never have known about the tweets Trump didn’t send.
If his staff can save him from trouble, even just a few times, their efforts will be worth it.
But no one can keep Trump from stirring up controversy.
Part of the problem is that in a White House made up of competing groups, people promote their worldviews and advance their causes by sending Trump material that may or may not be reliable.
Politico -- all about this story -- reported in May on the advisers&#39; penchant for strategically feeding the president questionable information.
Here&#39;s an example described by journalist Shane Goodmancher:
“Current and former Trump officials say Trump has a volcanic reaction to negative news clips, especially damaging leaks, as he frantically seeks to find out their source.
In late February, someone maliciously copied to the president an article from Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson’s website GotNews.com, which accused deputy chief of staff Katie Walsh of being “the source of numerous leaks” from the White House. , this was how Trump behaved at that time.
Even though Johnson has been permanently banned from Twitter for harassment, he has not provided any concrete evidence, and he has made numerous false accusations and later publicly denied them.
Trump read the article and then began asking officials about Walsh. &quot;
Goodmancher also said that then-chief of staff Reince Priebus and White House secretary Rob Porter &quot;tried to set up a system to manage and document the documents Trump received.&quot;
The results of it?
Kelly plans to do the same thing in three months.
Maybe he can prove to be a more effective administrator than Priebus, but Trump is still the same impulsive Trump, and his aides still compete with each other for influence.
These eternal influences will make Kelly&#39;s task even more difficult.
