Italy has warned NGOs operating migrant rescue ships in the Mediterranean that they will not be allowed to continue carrying out rescues unless they sign up to new operational regulations.
&quot;If NGOs do not sign up to the new code of conduct, it is difficult to see how they will survive,&quot; Interior Minister Marco Minniti told Turin daily La Stampa.
Minniti&#39;s warning came a day after Italian officials detained the crew of a ship belonging to the German aid group Youth Aid on suspicion that they were actually colluding with human traffickers to facilitate illegal immigration.
The aid group has only been in operation for a year and declined to comment on the specific subjects of the charges against Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
&quot;Saving lives is and will always be the most important thing to us, so we regret that we are currently unable to operate in the search and rescue area,&quot; the organization said in a statement on social media.
&quot;After all the information has been gathered, we can only assess all the allegations and the situation at this time.&quot;
Italian officials have been monitoring the Youth Rescue ship Iuventa since October.
Its crews are suspected of carrying migrants brought directly from small boats by human smugglers and allowing the smugglers to make hasty escapes and reuse the ship.
At least one such meeting allegedly took place at sea 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to prosecutors&#39; documents. The contents of the document were published by Italian media.
Its crew is suspected of flagrant disregard for the authority of the Italian Coast Guard, which oversees rescue operations in the area out of humanitarian fervor rather than any other motivation.
Ships such as the Iuventa apparently require an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities, as stipulated in the code of conduct.
Currently, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to abide by the code of conduct: Save the Children, the Malta-based Migrant Sea Aid Station and Spain&#39;s Pro-Activa Open Arms.
The latter said on Thursday that it believed the new regulations were unnecessary but acceptable because they would not bring any &quot;significant changes or obstacles&quot; to its rescue operations.
Among the organizations that refused to sign was the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
At the same time, Minniti said the number of migrants arriving in Italy had dropped sharply in recent weeks, a sign that efforts to beef up Libya&#39;s coast guard and unite local mayors were beginning to bear fruit.
&quot;In recent days, we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel,&quot; the minister said.
