Michelle Carter sentenced for text messages encouraging Conrad Roy to commit suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, 20, will serve 15 months in prison, which can be converted to probation after expiration. Additionally suspended for 5 years.
Carter was found guilty in June of the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy&#39;s father told Thursday&#39;s hearing: &quot;My family is heartbroken.
My son is my best friend. &quot;
Carter was allowed to remain free pending an appeal.
She faces up to 20 years in prison, but her lawyers believe both she and Mr Roy are mentally ill.
During the sentencing, Carter stood, wearing red trousers and a beige smock, with his hands clasped and his eyes looking downward through tears.
&quot;Her actions killed Conrad Roy,&quot; the prosecutor told the court.
“She took his life in order to live a better life for herself.
She failed to accept responsibility,&quot; prosecutors said.
&quot;She shows no remorse.&quot;
But Carter&#39;s lawyer said it was &quot;a horrific consequence that she deeply regrets.&quot;
However, Judge Lawrence Moniz said he did not find that her &quot;age or maturity, or even her mental illness, would have had any significant influence on her conduct.&quot;
A prosecutor read a statement from Roy&#39;s mother, Lynn Roy, who said, &quot;Not a day goes by that I don&#39;t grieve the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and everything I do. I am trying to stand with his sisters in all of my pain that will be with us forever,&quot; the statement said.
Mr. Roy&#39;s sister, Camdyn Roy, testified that she was &quot;devastated&quot; by the realization that she would never be able to attend her brother&#39;s wedding or be an aunt to his children.
&quot;Losing someone who has been with me since birth is a pain that I will live with for the rest of my life,&quot; she said.
The case appears to set a legal precedent because Massachusetts law does not criminalize encouraging another person to commit suicide.
In 2014, Roy was found dead of carbon monoxide poisoning in his car; Carter was 17 years old that year.
The case drew national attention after Carter&#39;s text messages revealed she encouraged him to commit suicide.
&quot;Hang yourself, jump off a building, stab yourself, there are many ways,&quot; she said in several text messages sent two weeks before his death while he was on holiday with his family.
&quot;You need to do this, Conrad,&quot; she wrote in the period before his suicide, &quot;all you have to do is start the generator and you will be free and happy.&quot;
Judge Moniz said Carter used Mr Roy&#39;s death to gain attention and ordered her not to profit from the case through any media.
There is a difference of legal opinion in this case.
One of Carter&#39;s few defenders was Amanda Knox, who was accused of murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007 and was acquitted two years later.
&quot;Michelle Carter deserves compassion and help, not jail time,&quot; Ms. Knox, 30, said in an op-ed published in the Los Angeles Times.
