China&#39;s self-driving tourism market size may exceed one trillion yuan in 2020
[Abstract] Against the backdrop of consumption upgrades and the prevalence of independent travel, self-driving travel is encouraged by national policies and favored by more and more consumers.
But at the same time, the self-driving travel market, which is expected to exceed one trillion in scale, is also facing dual challenges.
Against the background of consumption upgrades and the prevalence of independent travel, self-driving travel is encouraged by national policies and favored by more and more consumers.
But at the same time, the self-driving travel market, which is expected to exceed one trillion yuan, is also facing dual challenges. On the one hand, the development of the self-driving travel industry is not proportional to market demand. Self-driving travel organizers such as self-driving travel clubs and travel agencies are facing the dilemma of meager profits. On the other hand, the infrastructure and services faced by self-driving tours are still in their infancy.
Accounting for 60% of the total number of domestic tourists, the market size is expected to exceed one trillion
In 2016, there were 4.44 billion domestic tourists, and self-driving tours accounted for about 60% of the total domestic tourists. By 2020, the size of the self-driving tour market is expected to exceed one trillion.
According to statistics from the China Tourist Vehicle and Boat Association on the number of self-driving travelers, the number of self-driving travelers has continued to grow in the past five years, and the number of self-driving travelers has stabilized at more than half of the domestic tourist population.
At the same time, various regions and national levels have shown more attention and support to the emerging field of self-driving travel. From 2016 to 2017, policies and regulations related to self-driving, RV and camping tourism were intensively promulgated.
In July 2017, eight departments including the National Tourism Administration and the State Sports General Administration jointly issued the &quot;Development Plan for Self-Driving Sports Camps&quot;; in the same month, 14 departments including the National Development and Reform Commission and the Ministry of Finance jointly issued the &quot;Action Plan to Promote the Development of Rural Tourism and Improve Quality and Upgrading&quot; (2017)&quot;, self-driving travel was highlighted.
The introduction of the policy provides opportunities and policy guidance for the development of domestic self-driving tourism.
Self-driving travel clubs have meager profits, but a complete industrial chain is the key
Although the domestic self-driving travel market has huge potential and is actively guided by national policies, the self-driving travel industry is still in its infancy.
According to the &quot;2016-2017 China Self-Driving Travel Annual Development Report&quot;, there are thousands of domestic self-driving travel clubs, car clubs, car clubs, etc., but the majority of tourists arrange self-driving trips on their own. Tourists from various institutions such as travel clubs account for only about 15%.
At the same time, there are only a handful of online travel companies and traditional travel agencies that independently develop self-driving travel products. Many online travel platforms only sell self-driving travel products provided by some suppliers, and some self-driving travel clubs are also important suppliers.
In terms of organizing self-driving tour activities, it covers multiple aspects of &quot;food, accommodation, transportation, travel, shopping, and entertainment&quot;. It is highly fragmented, has a heavy upstream supply chain, and is highly random in tourist consumption.
Li Guanjie, founder and CEO of Beijing Xingtianxia Automobile Club, believes that self-driving travel clubs are essentially similar to travel agencies. The main profit model in the early days was mainly offline activities, with the core points being self-driving travel route products and group leadership services.
However, in the field of self-driving tours, the route products are now highly homogeneous and the service levels of tour leaders are uneven. Self-driving tour clubs are facing the need to transform again.
It can be seen that self-driving travel itself is not an independent industry. Instead, the displacement characteristics of self-driving travel have formed a cross-regional and industry ecosystem. It is very important to form a complete industrial chain.
Experts point out that in addition to basic tourism consumption, experience is a more important consumption element.
Therefore, for the development of the self-driving travel industry, the experience characteristics should be enhanced, and the theme of &quot;self-driving travel +&quot; and the IP of self-driving travel products should be developed.
Scenic roads are not just roads, car campsites should not only satisfy food and accommodation
Facing the rise of self-driving travel, the development of basic supporting facilities for self-driving travel is also still relatively rudimentary.
Li Guanjie pointed out that the tourist scenic route is not just a road, but needs to integrate transportation and tourism elements. However, road construction and tourism itself are the responsibility of two departments. The transportation department still remains at the same level when adding tourism elements. The construction of toilets, information centers, publicity boards and other facilities is not well integrated with tourism.
Compared with the well-known self-driving tour route &quot;U.S. Highway 66&quot;, the construction experience is worth learning from.
The design of scenic byways is no longer the most direct and fastest path between the departure point and the destination, but follows the design concept of &quot;experience the joy of driving&quot; to provide self-driving tourists with the best enjoyment of the beautiful scenery along the road; scenic byways can combine point-shaped, The connection of the planar tourist landscapes not only retains the historical and cultural value of the eco-tourism resources along the route, but also can hold various themed activities to enhance tourists&#39; participation and recreational experience, and create economic benefits for the local tourism industry.
In addition to scenic routes, campsites are also important supporting facilities for self-driving tours.
However, among the self-driving tourists that the Beijing News reporter knows, not many choose to stay in campsites.
They believe that many campsites tend to be in infrastructure and can only meet the needs of food and accommodation. They are not high-grade and have a single product, which cannot meet the needs of self-driving tours, which include many elements.
Industry insiders who did not want to be named said that in the past few years, many companies that set up camps were to acquire land. After acquiring the land, the subsequent supporting infrastructure construction and services did not keep up. Many operating conditions were losses, and there was no With later capital injection, it will be difficult to make some corresponding supporting products.
Consumers
According to data released by the China Tourist Vehicle and Vessel Association in 2017, in terms of age, self-driving travel groups are concentrated between the ages of 21 and 40, especially those between 31 and 40 years old. This group of people has a certain economic foundation and is interested in personalization. The demand for travel is high, and most of them are family travel customers.
According to the accommodation survey, self-driving tourists prefer non-standard accommodation.
From the perspective of self-driving travel types, self-driving in peripheral areas is the most important type of self-driving travel, accounting for 84.32%.
Self-driving abroad is a dream of many people, but the proportion is still relatively small.
At the same time, with the increase in consumer demand, tourists who used to like to &quot;visit scenic spots&quot; by self-driving have begun to change their concept. They no longer &quot;get off the car to take pictures and get in the car to sleep&quot; during self-driving travel, but pay more attention to the experience and process of travel.
Dinosaurs used camouflage to hide from enemies
At first glance, it looks scary, but it looks like a statue.
Researchers have released the first study of the incredible fossil of a rhinoceros-sized creature discovered by Canadian miners, saying the fossil is so well preserved that experts have dubbed it the &quot;Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.&quot;
This fossil is so well preserved that the color of its scaly skin can even be determined to be reddish brown. This shows that it has had some &quot;troublesome experiences.&quot;
A report in the journal Current Biology describes it as &quot;the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever discovered and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.&quot;
The fossil is a newly discovered nodosaur species that lived during the mid-Cretaceous period 110 million to 112 million years ago.
Its extremely well-preserved state stunned researchers, who described it as &quot;truly breathtaking.&quot;
According to National Geographic Magazine, this herbivorous armored dinosaur fossil is the best-preserved dinosaur fossil of its kind ever discovered.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while mining at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
At that time, he came across something that seemed different from the surrounding rocks, so he decided to take a closer look.
Afterwards, the fossils he found were sent to Canada&#39;s Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
It took researchers six years to reveal the beast hidden inside the 2,500-pound (1,100-kilogram) clod of earth.
After all this hard work, the final results can now be announced.
&quot;If you looked at it, you would almost believe it was sleeping,&quot; said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum. The creature is on display in the exhibition hall
&quot;It will become one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens in the history of science - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.&quot;
By studying its skin, researchers found that the herbivorous creature, although armored like a walking tank, would have been under significant threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and employed a concealment technique known as &quot;countershading&quot; that is also used by many modern animals.
In this way, it was better able to blend in with its surroundings and avoid enemies, suggesting it was preyed upon by larger dinosaurs, experts say.
The 110-million-year-old creature, a member of the nodosaur family, first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
After museum technician Mark Mitchell, who was part of the team, spent 7,000 hours painstakingly unveiling the beast, researchers are now studying it and naming it Borealopelta markmitchelli &quot;.
The specimens were so well preserved that Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to record the pattern and shape of the scales and armor on the body.
They discovered &quot;countershading,&quot; a common form of defense in the animal kingdom, which means the creature&#39;s back is darker than its sides.
Although countershading is common, the findings were surprising because the dinosaur was much larger than existing animals that used countershading.
This dinosaur faced the pressure of being hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs and evolved in a favorable direction, allowing it to hide from the confrontation as a means of survival.
But most living animals that use countershading, such as deer, zebras or armadillos, are prey-like small and fragile, suggesting the creatures face real pressures to survive.
&quot;The rampant predation of large, heavily armored dinosaurs shows just how dangerous the Cretaceous carnivorous dinosaurs were,&quot; Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in its scales also showed the dinosaur&#39;s skin was reddish-brown in color.
Scientists are continuing to study clues to the creature&#39;s life, including the stomach contents it retained to find out what was last eaten.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river when it died, was then washed into the sea, and finally sank to the bottom of the sea on its back.
At the time, Alberta&#39;s climate was as warm as southern Florida&#39;s today, and rivers and oceans were probably farther inland than they are today.
&quot;This nodosaur is truly amazing because it is completely covered in preserved scaly skin and is preserved in two dimensions, preserving its original shape,&quot; Brown said.
&quot;So the shape of this creature now is almost the same as it was in the Cretaceous.
You don&#39;t have to use much imagination to recreate it; if you glance at it, you&#39;ll almost believe it&#39;s sleeping. &quot;
The Cretaceous period was a time when large, bipedal theropod dinosaurs roamed the Earth.
Although Tyrannosaurus rex is the king of dinosaurs, it did not appear until millions of years after the armored dinosaurs. The armored dinosaur may have been hunted by some of T. rex&#39;s ancestors.
They include Acrocanthosaurus, a behemoth that weighed 6 tons and was 38 feet (11.5 meters) long.
Scientists whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology believe that the nodosaur was washed out to sea after it died and then mummified in the mud.
On March 21, 2011, Sean Fink excavated the creature at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray, Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, with skin and armor intact from the nose to the buttocks.
The creatures average about 18 feet (5 meters) long and weigh up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
It has two 20-inch-long spikes protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe the herbivorous, armored dinosaur roamed what is now western Canada before being swept out to sea by flooded rivers.
However, this dinosaur was buried at the bottom of the sea and its armor was completely preserved.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that remnants of skin still cover the bumpy armor plates on the dinosaur&#39;s skull.
As Michael Greshko writes in National Geographic, this level of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it the more incredible it becomes.
Remaining fossilized skin still covers the mottled armor on the dinosaur&#39;s skull.
Its right forefoot is on its side, with its five toes splayed upward.
I can count its armor pieces. &quot;
