She saw a live feed of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another officer raises his rifle and screams: &quot;I&#39;m going to kill you all... the beasts.&quot;
&quot;This is not normal,&quot; Ferrell recalled saying.
&quot;This is not what we are accustomed to calling a typical murder.&quot;
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was so angry that I cried. &quot;
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father&#39;s house and decided that the two would head to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, &quot;Whose Streets?,&quot; opening in theaters Aug. 11.
This is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience, told from the perspective of the people who live in this community and fill the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter (dressed in a floral dress and tiara), the two revisited a topic they had discussed countless times before that morning - &quot;about the black experience and the black condition.&quot;
&quot;Do you remember what I taught you about when black people had to fight for what they believed in?&quot; she recalled.
&quot;We&#39;re going to Ferguson now because police killed an 18-year-old boy and that&#39;s not right.
I had to take her,&quot; Ferrell said later.
“What happened today is the... culmination of everything that has gone before.
She was to know, see and rise from this.
She needs to be well developed not only in activism and organizing, but also in understanding the different layers of the black experience and the black condition, and understanding what we must do to be free and liberated.
Even if I&#39;m lucky enough to provide her with experiences with racism that she hasn&#39;t personally experienced, she&#39;s no different than any other black girl.
I feel like I&#39;m doing her a disservice if I protect her in this matter. &quot;
Their first stop in Ferguson was at a field across from the police station on South Florissant Road. The site became a camp for activists as they awaited the outcome of Officer Darren Wilson&#39;s eventual dismissal of charges.
Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who made bagged lunches.
They prepared bags and were responsible for passing them to protesters.
Slowly, Ferrell began to develop a new kind of activism.
“My activism completely changed after August 9,” she says. As an undergraduate at Missouri State University in St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Nursing Students Association and focused on food justice and health disparities in the Black community.
“I had no organizational experience.
This is how it all came about. &quot;
A few weeks later, Ferrell met the film&#39;s co-director Sabah Folayan at a night parade.
Folayan said she and her director of photography, Lucas Alvarado Farrar, &quot;just wanted to document&quot; what happened.
A question came to Ferrell&#39;s mind: &quot;Are you trying to document or are you trying to find a story that you can exploit?&quot;
This suspicion stems from the many cases in which people - often white - enter a community to profit from its pain and resilience.
As Foleyan explained in a recent interview, &quot;We heard that people who were born and raised in Ferguson were not centering their voices, and we wanted to do that differently.&quot;
Folayang has been linked with co-director Damon Davis. Damon Davis is a regional artist known for his activism on death row.
His involvement led Ferrell, along with six other locals, to join the Whose Streets? project team and stick with him in the years after Brown was shot.
&quot;This documentary is not about someone speaking for us or talking to us, it&#39;s about us speaking,&quot; Davis said.
“My main focus is on how these characters are represented, because that’s how I’m represented.”
Although the goal was not to focus on Ferrell&#39;s experience – but rather to show that the movement was &quot;less about messianic leaders and more about community cohesion,&quot; Folayan says – she proved to be the most open of the film&#39;s participants.
As a result, &quot;Whose Streets?&quot; surprisingly chronicles Ferrell&#39;s personal life, falling in love and getting married.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell laughed when he first saw the finished product.
“But I understand that there has to be a level of vulnerability that goes into doing this work and humanizing Black people.”
Additionally, Ferrell’s story reaffirms and repositions the role of black queer women within the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement&#39;s three founders -- who coined #BlackLivesMatter on social media after the 2012 shooting of black teen Trayvon Martin -- identify as queer.
“Black queer women in leadership generally sustain this movement,” Ferrell said, “and that’s because we’re constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black queer women have to endure it all. &quot;
Folayan agreed, noting that &quot;this movement is really supported by black women and a lot of black queer women.&quot;
Ferrell was chosen to be the centerpiece of the film because of who she is. However, she insisted &quot;this is not affirmative action&quot;.
“She’s the one who inspires that energy,” she said.
&quot;Even though she&#39;s on the front lines, that&#39;s not a coincidence. Because you have so much going on as a black queer woman in these intersections of life.
You can feel her energy through the screen. &quot;
Meanwhile, in Ferguson, the news cameras are long gone, but tense racial relations between the community and police remain.
Ferrer was sentenced to more than two and a half years of probation for trying to block a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the sociopolitical climate in the area she calls home: &quot;It&#39;s a mess.&quot;
Still, she has stuck to the chants she strives to remember since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“We have a responsibility to fight for our freedom.
It is our responsibility to win.
We must love each other and support each other.
We have nothing to lose except our shackles. &quot;
