On the opposite wall is her mitochondrial DNA sequence, with Cs, Gs and As symbols scrawled in pencil.
By encompassing 200 letters (or nucleotides, each artist&#39;s complex scientific lexicon), Heather Dewey Harborg hopes that by painting these eerily similar portraits, she hopes to convey that, at least physiologically, everyone is the same of.
&quot;I want people to get over this, that our genome doesn&#39;t care who we are, how publicly available genetic data is interpreted, how subjective it is,&quot; says Heather Dewey Harbaugh of his 2007 video The work &quot;False Memories&quot; is also on display.
&quot;DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, so here are 30 of them.&quot;
The final work in the exhibition, In a Room , is a page from the previously illustrated novella.
It shows a flamboyant, King Kong-like Manning with a bullhorn in hand by an American soldier.
“When they bring your speech to a halt, they win,” reads the wall.
&quot;So don&#39;t shut up.&quot;
“It comes directly from a letter she wrote to me,” said the Philadelphia-based artist.
&quot;No matter how scared I am, I will still say it.&quot;
Manning has yet to see the exhibit in person, as is so foreseen in the comics, but when she does, she&#39;ll be masked by her own DNA portrait and be cheered on by a group of protesters in the center of the exhibit.
It&#39;s purposeful, too, as all the objects in the exhibit are built to the height (5.2 feet, Manning&#39;s height) of her genetic haplogroup information written in pencil.
&quot;In the past, I&#39;ve hung them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a group of people,&quot; Dewey Hagberg said of the portraits.
&quot;But I wanted them to feel like a group of protesters following Chelsea, just as people were protesting for her release.&quot;
