Chen Xinlei and Yang Kaihan: Amazon announced its entry into bookstores and grocery stores when it was squeezing into the world&#39;s top ten retailers. Both the timing and motivation are worth pondering.
In November 2015, Amazon opened its first physical bookstore in Seattle, followed by two more in Portland and San Diego.
At the beginning of 2017, Amazon opened a store in New York and plans to have at least eight stores by the end of the year.
Almost at the same time, Amazon announced the trial operation of its unmanned supermarket (Amazon Go). Customers do not need to queue or check out when entering the store. They can just scan the code when entering, take the desired products and leave, and the shopping amount will be automatically deducted from the customer&#39;s account. Debited from Amazon account.
As far as Amazon is concerned, it is very unexpected that it has suddenly made frequent moves in physical stores in recent years.
Because as early as 2007, in the &quot;Open Letter to Shareholders&quot;, CEO Jeff Bezos emphasized that Amazon will not easily open physical stores unless the following four conditions are met at the same time:
1. We must be convinced that this new opportunity can provide shareholders with a return on their investment;
2. We must be convinced that this new opportunity is of great significance to the entire company;
3. We must be convinced that this new opportunity is ignored by the market;
4. We must make sure that we have enough resources to make customer-oriented differentiation in this market.
Bookstores and grocery stores are the two most shaky categories in physical retail, and they were also the first competitors to fall after the rise of Amazon.
Amazon announced its entry into these two physical markets when it squeezed into the top ten retailers in the world. Both the timing and motivation are worth pondering.
Are Amazon’s actions contrary to the assurances in the shareholder letter?
Similar sounds were heard on the other side of the world. On the morning of October 13, 2016, at the 2016 Hangzhou Computing Conference, Jack Ma, Chairman of Alibaba’s Board of Directors, delivered a keynote speech.
He said: &quot;Starting next year, Alibaba will no longer mention the term &#39;e-commerce&#39;.
The era of pure e-commerce will soon end. In the next ten or twenty years, there will be no e-commerce and will be replaced by &#39;new retail&#39;.
Only when online, offline and logistics are combined can new retail be created. &quot;
For a time, the word &quot;new retail&quot; seemed to be cast by magic and was frequently mentioned by people in the industry.
But what exactly does “new retail” mean?
If it just refers to the combination of online and offline, then this concept is not new.
In 2016, eMarketer tracked the 180 largest e-commerce companies and estimated that total e-commerce sales were approximately US$200 billion, with the largest 25 accounting for more than US$159 billion.
Among these 25, 18 are traditional retailers that have only started operating online in the past five years (such as Macy&#39;s, Nordstrom, Target, Gap, etc.).
Alibaba Group’s 28.3 billion yuan investment in Suning Cloud Commerce is still fresh in our minds.
Globally, retailers and e-commerce are shifting from a single channel to an omni-channel retail system covering physical stores, e-commerce, mobile terminals and social media.
Could it be that Jack Ma’s mention of “new retail” is more of a summary than a prospect for the future?
If not, what is the difference between the concept of omni-channel and “new retail”?
Perhaps the key to the problem is not whether online and offline will be integrated, but how.
Looking back on the past 20 years in the retail industry, the rise of e-commerce is like the rise of discount retailers in the early years, both focusing on price and convenience.
Relying on these two pain points, e-commerce companies have moved highly standardized products, such as books and CDs, from offline to online.
With the development of online consumption habits and the continuous improvement of customer experience, e-commerce has extended its reach to other categories and begun to improve efficiency.
In the words of Alibaba CEO Zhang Yong, “Using Internet ideas and technology to comprehensively reform and upgrade the existing total of about 30 trillion social retailers, so that the increasingly upgraded consumption needs of Chinese consumers can be effectively met, making The entire process of commodity production, circulation, and services has become more efficient due to the widespread use of the Internet and big data.&quot;
Therefore, the path of e-commerce is one that is asset-light on the surface but asset-heavy in reality.
&quot;Light&quot; refers to the fact that the burdens of fixed assets, staffing, management processes, etc. are not as large as those of traditional retail; &quot;heavy&quot; refers to the huge investment required in logistics, warehousing, etc.
Changes in logistics methods have ensured the high efficiency of e-commerce.
