Startups that help your company avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett once wanted to survey employees at her e-commerce startup about their happiness, but the surveys didn&#39;t do much.
The responses you get are often unclear, unhelpful, or even worse, deceptive.
Even with her promise of anonymity, some employees remain distrustful of the process.
Errett, who oversees Madison Reed, a 75-person e-commerce hair care company in San Francisco, said there was a &quot;lack of consistency and objectivity in the responses.&quot;
So she called for help.
A new crop of HR startups are popping up to help companies understand how their employees are feeling.
They build and license software specifically designed to measure employee engagement, allowing companies to quickly poll specific teams and demographic groups, provide employees with anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass executives Reports directly to the Board of Directors.
&quot;Right now, you can track your fitness with tools like Strava and Fitbit, but where&#39;s the corporate Fitbit?&quot; said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint. Glint software analytics tool is used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Eret says that within three years, she&#39;s used Glint to gain more insights into her employees&#39; thoughts and feelings.
In addition to quick surveys and polls on specific teams, Glint provides company heat maps that show at a glance which units have the most complaints and which managers have low approval scores – allowing her to drill down to understand why.
Companies are starting to realize that they must master their workplace culture to avoid becoming the next Uber. Uber has been embroiled in scandal after former employees published a blog post describing an environment of harassment, and those speakers were punished by the company.
For startups like Glint, this desire for oversight is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to financial technology analysis website Let&#39;s Talk Payments, the global governance, regulatory and compliance industry is likely to be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based startup that helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw an increase in interest and activity during Uber&#39;s reputational damage earlier this year.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed on as a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent lets companies send customized &quot;diagnostic&quot; surveys, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of their problem areas.
Convercent also offers an anonymous text hotline for employees to report bad behavior.
If the chairman is implicated, the complaint will go directly to the board.
&quot;The court of public opinion has usurped the power of regulators,&quot; said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is found to have treated its employees poorly or acted unethically, even if regulators don&#39;t step in, the company could face costly consumer boycotts, employee turnover and involvement in lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees across more than 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees understand work guidelines and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate headquarters.
Previously, if employees wanted to report a problem, they had to find a company headquarters phone number or email, file a formal complaint, and hope headquarters would take it seriously.
It&#39;s often a daunting and uncomfortable experience, said James Vetrano, Ruby Tuesday&#39;s general counsel, who doesn&#39;t think there&#39;s a good way to track employee complaints.
But now the company is using Convercent to more quickly identify and address issues that executives in distant offices, cities or states were previously unaware of - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair wage practices.
“I get a closer, 360-degree view of the work experience,” said Vetrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday’s risk management team.
&quot;We are protecting our shareholders from employment litigation.&quot;
Quinlan said companies began to place a greater emphasis on ethics, values and employee engagement in 2002 after Andorra accounting firm collapsed due to ethical violations in the Enron scandal.
But it wasn’t until “social media came into its own” that companies realized they couldn’t stop their revelations from going viral online.
“Before using technology to monitor ethics, people looked at hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service and charge companies a recurring fee for use of the products.
This business model and business opportunity is backed by venture investors who are already backing both startups.
In February, Convercent raised $10 million in funding from the likes of Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing its total capital to $47 million.
In November, Glint received $10 million in funding from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing its total funding to $60 million.
Given the interconnectedness between companies, culture and venture capital, these investments come as little surprise.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees have higher expectations of the workplace than before.
In a competitive market like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are just table stakes.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted, valued, and that their time is being spent with a company that has a positive mission.
“When people enjoy joining a company, feel their voices are heard, and the work they do is beneficial, they are more committed to making the company successful,” Nina McCartney, Vice President of Global Benefits and Employee Experience at LinkedIn express. LinkedIn uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors realize returns when their portfolio companies perform well; companies perform well when their employees are loyal and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no wonder they’re looking for financial support.
Workplace culture experts say it’s important to have data on employee engagement.
However, this data is useless unless the company&#39;s administrators take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, you can expect that the company is undergoing change.
If change doesn&#39;t happen fast enough, or at all, it can lead to disappointment and lead to employees disengaging from the company.
&quot;If you&#39;re asking for 4,000 pieces of advice, you need to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations,&quot; said Russell Rath, head of consulting at business management firm Cort International, who has seen companies rely too much on data collection. mistake.
“Because if you don’t follow through, employees are going to think, ‘Did you really hear what I said?
Do you care?
If you don&#39;t care, why should I care? &#39;&quot;
Errett said Madison Reed now conducts monthly employee surveys and has been able to take action the same day Glint reports an issue.
After gathering feedback from employees about their frustrations with the speed of decision-making and quality of communication, she was able to fix the problem by restructuring the team within the company and adding communication training.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new insights into its workforce and, in the long term, hopes to make a shift to better retain employees in an industry known for high attrition rates.
“If you’re not committed to creating a culture of transparency, you’re going to lose talent,” Vetrano said.
“If you lose talent, you lose customers.
And when you lose customers, you lose the company. &quot;
