Could eating less meat, dairy and chocolate help relieve inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)?
Meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study suggests just the opposite: A diet rich in meat protein and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease affects the lives of about 1.3 million Americans and 300,000 Britons, causing stomach cramps and bloating, frequent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme tiredness.
Researchers at the University of Washington typically advise patients to avoid meat and dairy to relieve symptoms, but researchers found that protein&#39;s key amino acid tryptophan helps promote the growth of immune cells that promote tolerance in the gut. force.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells patrol the gut to ensure that harmful microorganisms hidden in food do not sneak into the body.
Maintaining a balance between cells that trigger inflammation and cells that promote tolerance, protecting the body without damaging various sensitive and fragile tissues.
When the balance shifts too far toward inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
In experiments, a type of immune-promoting cells was found in mice carrying special bacteria.
Bacteria need tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to give their cells their appearance.
Professor Colonna said: &quot;We established a link between a bacterial population (Lactobacillus reuteri, which is a normal part of the gut microbiota) and the development of a cell population that promotes tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice consumed in their diet, the more immune cells they had.
He suggested that if the same approach were used in humans, combining L. reuteri with a tryptophan-rich diet might result in a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment.
Postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas was studying a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she discovered that one group of research mice had such cells, but another group did not. strains when reared separately.
She suspects the difference is related to the mice&#39;s gut microbial communities (the bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract).
DNA sequencing of the mice&#39;s cholesterol revealed six bacterial species that were present in mice with immune cells but not in mice without immune cells.
Mice are raised in a sterile environment, so they lack gut microbes and cannot develop the immune cells that are produced in the presence of Lactobacillus reuteri.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew Lactobacillus reuteri in fluid and then transferred small amounts of the bacteria-free fluid to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
The immune cells develop into tolerant cells.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it was shown that the active ingredient was a by-product of tryptophan metabolism called indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice&#39;s diet, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri in our gastrointestinal tracts.
It is not yet known whether humans can use the tryptophan byproduct from Lactobacillus reuteri to induce cell development in the same way as in mice, but tryptophan-related gene defects have been found in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
&quot;The development of these cells may be exactly what we want because these cells control the inflammatory response on the lining of the gut,&quot; she said.
It is not certain that the high levels of tryptophan present in L. reuteri may lead to an increase in the number of this species.
