China&#39;s household debt ratio is close to that of the United States. What&#39;s more terrifying than not being able to buy a house is not being able to repay the debt?
Recently, everyone has been discussing the recent changes in real estate policy. Is the real estate policy going to be loosened again? Will the diversification of land policy supply entities lead to a decline in housing prices?
However, when we are worried about real estate prices, macroeconomic regulation, and the future trend of the real estate market, the &quot;People&#39;s Daily&quot; has written an article again. Last time we specifically discussed the &quot;People&#39;s Daily&quot; commentary on setting the tone for real estate regulation, and now &quot;People&#39;s Daily&quot; The People&#39;s Daily article discusses a more serious topic than whether you can afford a house. This is, even if you can afford a house, can you still afford the debt?
Today, let’s talk about a more serious problem than buying a house: loan repayment.
1. China’s increasingly serious housing debt crisis
The overseas edition of &quot;People&#39;s Daily&quot; published a commentary article &quot;Awards and Loans: Joys and Worries of Struggling Youth&quot; on January 17. According to the data in the article, in November 2017, the National Finance and Development Laboratory of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, The &quot;Report on China&#39;s Deleveraging Process in the Third Quarter&quot; released by the National Balance Sheet Research Center pointed out that the household sector&#39;s leverage ratio continued its upward trend, rising from 47.4% in the second quarter of 2017 to 48.6% in the third quarter, an increase of 1.3 percentage points. It rose by 3.8 percentage points in the first three quarters of 2017.
The proportion of debt of the residential sector in the entire real economy has increased, and the leverage ratio has increased rapidly.
Relevant research shows that the liabilities of Chinese households in financial institutions are mainly consumer loans, accounting for about two-thirds of residents&#39; liabilities, which is about twice that of operating loans.
Among them, medium- and long-term loans, mainly housing loans, account for about 80% of consumer loans. However, in terms of incremental growth, short-term consumer loans are growing faster than medium- and long-term loans.
In addition, China&#39;s household debt rate only counts the total amount of credit obtained by the household sector from financial institutions. However, Chinese households also have many private loans, including borrowing money from relatives and friends, and there is a large amount of hidden debt.
Seeing such data, people can&#39;t help but be a little stunned. According to statistics from Suning Financial Research Institute, China&#39;s residents&#39; leverage ratio was only 3% in 1996 and only 18% in 2008. However, since 2008, the residents&#39; leverage ratio has begun to show Rapid growth, doubling in just six years to 36.4%. By the third quarter of 2017, the household leverage ratio had reached 48.6%.
Let’s compare another data. In May last year, HSBC released a survey report spanning nine countries with nearly tens of thousands of respondents.
This report interviewed &quot;millennial&quot; young people (born between 1980 and 2000) in nine countries.
The report pointed out that the home ownership rate of young people born in the 1980s and 1990s in China is as high as 70%, far ahead of the second-placed Mexico (46%), and twice the level of the United States (35%).
These data tell us a very likely problem, that is, compared with being unable to afford a house, the biggest potential &quot;grey rhinoceros&quot; for Chinese residents at this stage is probably the inability to repay their debts.
2. Why is the housing debt crisis the most serious problem?
As in our previous analysis, although we have been saying that China&#39;s housing prices are relatively high, compared to other countries in the world, China&#39;s home ownership rate is actually quite high. So rather than saying that housing prices are high and people cannot afford to buy a house, I&#39;m afraid The question I want to ask many of my friends now is, can you afford the loan?
We look at the real estate market around the world. Due to its late start, China&#39;s real estate market has not yet experienced a major real estate crisis except Hainan, which we mentioned before. However, just ten years ago in 2008, the origin of the global financial tsunami It’s America’s housing crisis.
The cause of the U.S. real estate crisis is blamed on Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
In the golden age of the United States, real estate companies sold houses to low-income people in the United States with extremely low down payments in order to expand sales. When the U.S. economy was improving, the real estate market was also booming. However, the good times did not last long. The growth of the U.S. economy has stagnated, causing home buyers&#39; incomes to fall, and a large number of household consumption expenditures have begun to decline.
However, the current situation in the United States at that time was that American household assets were composed of financial assets and real estate assets. Almost all household assets of low-income groups in the United States were real estate, while most of the assets of the top 20% of high-income groups were financial assets. As a result, the poorer the households in the United States, the higher their real estate debt ratio.
A serious fact is that these people bought their houses when the economy was better, so the money to pay the mortgage is also calculated based on their better income. When the income declines, the pressure on the mortgage is not reduced or even reduced. Because some subprime mortgage plans became more volatile, the real estate problems of these American families gradually evolved into a real estate crisis.
As a result, some people could not afford to pay their mortgages because their incomes were too low, so banks began to repossess properties. When banks repossessed properties from home buyers who defaulted on their loans, they sold them at extremely low prices, which led to a step-by-step increase in housing prices in the area. decline, this process triggered a further decline in housing prices, forming a vicious cycle. When housing prices fell to a certain level, more and more home buyers found that the value of their houses was even lower than their loans, so As a result, more people stopped paying off their mortgages, resulting in more bad debts.
As a result, a huge vicious circle was formed:
&quot;The economy is in recession - incomes are falling - some people can&#39;t repay their mortgages - banks sell the houses of debtors at low prices - house prices fall - more people stop paying mortgages - banks sell again - house prices fall again …”
And the problem is not just that, because house prices continue to fall, people stop repaying loans and give the house to the bank. It does not mean that you will have no debt. If the money obtained by the bank from auctioning the house can repay the loan you owe the bank, then you still need to Then repay the money. To put it simply, suppose you bought a house worth 3 million with a down payment of 600,000 and a loan of 2.4 million. When the house price dropped to the point where the house was only worth 2 million, you stopped paying back the loan and gave the house away. Bank, after the bank auctions the house, you not only lose your down payment of 600,000, but also owe the bank a debt of 400,000, and you still have to pay back the money.
As a result, under such vicious cycles one after another, the U.S. economy gradually collapsed, eventually triggering the 2008 financial crisis in the United States.
Therefore, the current level of China&#39;s household debt ratio has reached a high of 46.8%, which is an issue that requires great vigilance. This data is still lower than the level of developed countries at present, but signs of the problem have begun to appear. The country started last year The repeated emphasis on deleveraging is a very prescient judgment. If the household debt ratio is allowed to continue to rise, it will inevitably cause huge risks, so we must strictly guard against the emergence of financial risks.
Therefore, with the positioning that houses are for living in and not for speculation, the country has quickly established multiple measures such as multi-subject supply, multi-channel guarantee, and simultaneous rental and purchase to further resolve potential risks.
For our individual families, we must abandon the speculative thinking in real estate and act according to our ability when buying a house to prevent our family from falling into a huge burden. Only by rationally evaluating our own income and debt levels can we develop a healthy family wealth. .
Author: Special researcher at Suning Financial Research Institute, financial columnist, and financial commentator.
