White House props cost thousands
According to military records released by Time magazine, the White House decided last month to transport a Marine Corps helicopter to the South Lawn to highlight the great glory of American manufacturing, at a cost of up to $24,000.
The green and white Sikorsky VH-3D (also known as Marine One when the president is aboard) was an important exhibit at the White House event on July 17 highlighting American construction projects.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured manufacturing products from all 50 states.
Exhibits include a Connecticut-made helicopter, a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a Mississippi forklift.
According to records from Marine Helicopter Flight Group 1 (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter, the White House Military Office requested that the helicopter be present under routine orders (FRAGO), which is when the helicopter landed on the South Lawn for the &quot; Only 36 hours before the special” event.
&quot;I just wanted to make sure you were aware, as this event is taken very seriously,&quot; the HMX-1 commander said in an email to his superior, the Marine Corps&#39; deputy commandant of flight, the day before the event.
The information indicates that the helicopter will arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. event, and will not leave until the lawn is cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that evening.
The information also stated that in the event of a delay in departure from the White House, a second crew would be required for the return flight due to duty time constraints.
The original crew was on standby at the helicopter during the event, while security force personnel were nearby while the aircraft was on the ground.
Records obtained by TIME did not make it clear whether a second crew was ultimately needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
Records state that HMX-1 asked whether the event violated the Act.
&quot;One question we asked was whether this was a violation of the Hatch Act and were told it was not,&quot; the commander wrote.
&quot;Sounds like you&#39;re locked up,&quot; the deputy commander replied.
The White House defines the Made in America event as an official event and therefore not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president pushed for what was then a Senate issue: health care reform and touted controls on government regulations.
Using Marine One or Air Force One for political propaganda purposes is nothing new.
Successive presidents have been required to travel on these planes.
But requisitioning them solely for photographic purposes is uncommon.
Trump came into the spotlight in February, as his presidential plane taxied to the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with criticism of his predecessor&#39;s use of the plane. complaint information.
&quot;The White House is excited about this &#39;Made in America&#39; exhibit, which showcases products from all 50 states and made by American workers using American materials,&quot; said White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights near the Washington area and on the South Lawn, practicing accurately placing the President of the United States at the White House.
HMX-1 practiced 58 landings at the White House while Trump was in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July.
An official said the Made in America event flight counts toward crew training requirements this month.
The helicopter unit also flew an additional 11 hours of &quot;non-presidential support missions&quot; that day.
The White House said taxpayers were not footing the bill for any other props at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in arranging the South Lawn helicopter display.
HMX-1 did not keep budget records for presidential flights, so determining the exact costs incurred by the event is difficult.
But according to DOD hourly rate records for fiscal year 2017, the DOD reimbursable cost for the VH-3D was $24,380 per flight hour.
Troop records record each flight taking 30 minutes from the aircraft&#39;s base at Marine Corps Air Station Quantico, Virginia.
The White House said the cost of operating the helicopter was far less than that.
&quot;Estimates of taxpayer costs based on reimbursement are very misleading,&quot; Walters said.
These estimated costs include personnel, maintenance and many other sunk costs included in the annual appropriation.
A 2015 RAND study showed that DoD reimbursement does not include personnel costs, but it does include fuel, maintenance and contracting costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the event,
&quot;The idea is to showcase something made in America this week,&quot; he said.
And I know Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are proud of the fact that they both contribute to our national security, and I&#39;m guessing hundreds, if not thousands, of people&#39;s jobs depend on it.
And I think like most Americans, we&#39;re all very proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, which are the result of the hard work of countless Americans.
So it&#39;s certainly not out of place to highlight this. &quot;
It&#39;s unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter as he toured the South Lawn at the event, but he did get into the driver&#39;s seat of the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives and joked with the media about his own planes from the company.
&quot;I know Sikorsky aircraft very well. I have three of them,&quot; he said.
