The union wants management of biscuit maker McVitie&#39;s to guarantee a long-term commitment to production at its Glasgow factory.
The Scottish branch of the General Trade Union said the company had been silent on the future of investment in the Tollcross plant.
The factory has more than 500 employees and produces products such as oatmeal biscuits (Hobnobs) and rich tea biscuits (Rich tea).
McVitie&#39;s owner Pladis said the company had invested more than £5 million in the factory over the past few years.
He added that if there are changes to factory operations, employees and union representatives &quot;will be the first to know.&quot;
In a letter to the company&#39;s directors, the Scottish branch of the General Trade Union called on McVitie&#39;s to &quot;address the issue of funds not being transferred to modernize its production lines.&quot;
Drew Duffy, senior organizer of the General Workers&#39; Union, said: &quot;Our members are deeply concerned that we have not been able to get a clear understanding of Tollcross&#39;s future business needs and investment plans from the factory general manager. worry.
Generations of families work here, and the high concentration of labor within the local community and greater Glasgow area is an important pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Therefore, from a jobs, pay and economic prosperity perspective, against the backdrop of Brexit, rising costs of living and a long-term decline in manufacturing, there is an urgent need for McVitie&#39;s to continue to expand its production network in the east area of Glasgow. &quot;
A spokesman for Pradis said: &quot;The director of Tollcross received a letter from the Scottish branch of the General Workers&#39; Union yesterday and the company will respond immediately because we value maintaining contact with employees and union representatives. Continuous contact.
Two months ago we held a regular meeting with employees and AGM representatives in Tollcross where a number of issues were discussed openly.
We held discussions with our employees and then, like all other companies operating in a highly competitive and economically uncertain environment, we conducted a review of the ongoing operating model we apply across our businesses and plants in order to remain competitive.
She added: “We have invested more than £5 million at our Tollcross site in recent years, particularly in production line and operational improvements.
